25|$|The {{drinking}} bird is a <b>heat</b> <b>engine</b> that exploits {{a temperature}} difference to convert heat energy to a pressure difference within the device, and performs mechanical work. Like all heat engines, the drinking bird works through a thermodynamic cycle. The initial {{state of the}} system is a bird with a wet head oriented vertically.|$|E
25|$|Dichloromethane (DCM, or {{methylene}} chloride) is {{an organic}} compound with the formula CH2Cl2. This colorless, volatile liquid with a moderately sweet aroma {{is widely used}} as a solvent. Although it is not miscible with water, it is miscible with many organic solvents. One of the most well-known applications of dichloromethane is in the drinking bird <b>heat</b> <b>engine.</b>|$|E
